JCA sits back in his corner office at Darseny College. It's a large room with two tall windows letting in a lot of natural light and overlooking the campus's Community garden managed by professors and student teaching assistants and worked by botany, biology, and agricultural science majors. On the sill of each window is a line of terracotta pots, each with different types of edible plants growing out of them. On the wall hangs his diplomas: a bachelor's from Darseny College, a Master's from Patrium Central University, and a PhD from University of Georgia, as well as a picture of a teenage JCA with his arm around Murray Bookchin. On his big, wooden desk sits a giant bushy lavender plant, a flowering pink hibiscus bush, a big ornamental tea pot, a few pictures of his wife and twin babies, and his laptop, where he's splitting time between writing up syllabi for the summer semester's classes and drafting plans for sustainable public garden projects, which would help the island hold out under siege. A small black and tan dachshund sleeps in a dog bed in one of the office's corners. (edited)
